# Pixel-art scaling algorithms - Wikipedia

> ## Excerpt
> Pixel art scaling algorithms are graphical filters that attempt to enhance the appearance of hand-drawn 2D pixel art graphics. These algorithms are a form of automatic image enhancement. Pixel art scaling algorithms employ methods significantly different than the common methods of image rescaling, which have the goal of preserving the appearance of images.

---
[![](data:image/png;base64,)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:2xsai_example.svg)

Sprite of a television set (center) resized using simple nearest-neighbor scaling (left) and the 2xSaI interpolation algorithm (right)

[![](data:image/png;base64,)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Pixel-Art_Scaling_Comparison.png)

Comparison of common pixel art scaling algorithms. View in full resolution to see the differences.

**Pixel art scaling algorithms** are graphical filters that attempt to enhance the appearance of hand-drawn 2D [pixel art](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel_art "Pixel art") graphics. These [algorithms](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algorithm "Algorithm") are a form of automatic image enhancement. Pixel art scaling algorithms employ methods significantly different than the common methods of [image rescaling](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Image_rescaling "Image rescaling"), which have the goal of preserving the appearance of images.

As pixel art graphics are commonly used at very low [resolutions](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Image_resolution "Image resolution"), they employ careful coloring of individual pixels. This results in graphics that rely on a high amount of stylized visual cues to define complex shapes. Several specialized algorithms<sup id="cite_ref-1"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel-art_scaling_algorithms#cite_note-1"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> have been developed to handle re-scaling of such graphics.

These specialized algorithms can improve the appearance of pixel-art graphics, but in doing so they introduce changes. Such changes may be undesirable, especially if the goal is to faithfully reproduce the original appearance.

Since a typical application of this technology is improving the appearance of [fourth-generation](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_video_game_consoles_(fourth_generation) "History of video game consoles (fourth generation)") and earlier [video games](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Video_game "Video game") on [arcade and console emulators](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Video_game_console_emulator "Video game console emulator"), many pixel art scaling algorithms are designed to run in real-time for sufficiently small input images at 60-[frames per second](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frames_per_second "Frames per second"). This places constraints on the type of [programming](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_programming "Computer programming") techniques that can be used for this sort of real-time processing.<sup>[<i><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="Unclear what constraints this refers to as scaling algorithms can usually be parallelized and the source resolution would be low. (June 2023)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> Many work only on specific scale factors. 2 is the most common scale factor, while and 3, 4, 5, and 6 exist but are less used.

### SAA5050 'Diagonal Smoothing'

\[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Pixel-art_scaling_algorithms&action=edit&section=2 "Edit section: SAA5050 'Diagonal Smoothing'")\]

The [Mullard SAA5050](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mullard_SAA5050 "Mullard SAA5050") Teletext character generator chip (1980) used a primitive pixel scaling algorithm to generate higher-resolution characters on the screen from a lower-resolution representation from its internal [ROM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Read-only_memory "Read-only memory"). Internally, each character shape was defined on a 59 pixel grid, which was then interpolated by smoothing diagonals to give a 1018 pixel character, with a characteristically angular shape, surrounded to the top and the left by two pixels of blank space. The algorithm only works on monochrome source data, and assumes the source pixels will be logically true or false depending on whether they are 'on' or 'off'. Pixels 'outside the grid pattern' are assumed to be off.<sup id="cite_ref-2"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel-art_scaling_algorithms#cite_note-2"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-3"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel-art_scaling_algorithms#cite_note-3"><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-4"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel-art_scaling_algorithms#cite_note-4"><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup>

The algorithm works as follows:

```
A B C --\ 1 2
D E F --/ 3 4

1 = B | (A &amp; E &amp; !B &amp; !D)
2 = B | (C &amp; E &amp; !B &amp; !F)
3 = E | (!A &amp; !E &amp; B &amp; D)
4 = E | (!C &amp; !E &amp; B &amp; F) 
```

Note that this algorithm, like the Eagle algorithm below, has a flaw: If a pattern of 4 pixels in a hollow diamond shape appears, the hollow will be obliterated by the expansion. The SAA5050's internal character ROM carefully avoids ever using this pattern.

The degenerate case:

```
  *
 * *
  *
```

becomes:

```
   **
  ****
 ******
 ******
  ****
   **
```

### EPX/Scale2/AdvMAME2

\[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Pixel-art_scaling_algorithms&action=edit&section=3 "Edit section: EPX/Scale2/AdvMAME2")\]

Eric's Pixel Expansion (EPX) is an algorithm developed by [Eric Johnston](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Eric_Johnston_(engineer)&action=edit&redlink=1 "Eric Johnston (engineer) (page does not exist)") at [LucasArts](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LucasArts "LucasArts") around 1992, when porting the [SCUMM](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SCUMM "SCUMM") engine games from the IBM PC (which ran at 320200256 colors) to the early color Macintosh computers, which ran at more or less double that resolution.<sup id="cite_ref-mactech_5-0"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel-art_scaling_algorithms#cite_note-mactech-5"><span>[</span>5<span>]</span></a></sup> The algorithm works as follows, expanding P into 4 new pixels based on P's surroundings:

[![The EPX algorithm expands pixel P into four new pixels.](data:image/png;base64,)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:EPX_Algorithm_Diagram.png "The EPX algorithm expands pixel P into four new pixels.")

```
 1=P; 2=P; 3=P; 4=P;
 IF C==A =&gt; 1=A
 IF A==B =&gt; 2=B
 IF D==C =&gt; 3=C
 IF B==D =&gt; 4=D
 IF of A, B, C, D, three or more are identical: 1=2=3=4=P
```

Later implementations of this same algorithm (as AdvMAME2 and Scale2, developed around 2001) are slightly more efficient but functionally identical:

```
 1=P; 2=P; 3=P; 4=P;
 IF C==A AND C!=D AND A!=B =&gt; 1=A
 IF A==B AND A!=C AND B!=D =&gt; 2=B
 IF D==C AND D!=B AND C!=A =&gt; 3=C
 IF B==D AND B!=A AND D!=C =&gt; 4=D
```

AdvMAME2 is available in [DOSBox](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DOSBox "DOSBox") via the `scaler=advmame2x` [dosbox.conf](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Configuration_file "Configuration file") option.

The AdvMAME4/Scale4 algorithm is just EPX applied twice to get 4 resolution.

#### Scale3/AdvMAME3 and ScaleFX

\[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Pixel-art_scaling_algorithms&action=edit&section=4 "Edit section: Scale3/AdvMAME3 and ScaleFX")\]

[![](data:image/png;base64,)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:EPX-neep.png)

EPX can be used to scale bitmap fonts. From top to bottom: a) original font size; b) nearest-neighbor 2 scaling; c) EPX 2 scaling; d) nearest-neighbor 3 scaling; e) EPX 3 scaling.

The AdvMAME3/Scale3 algorithm (available in [DOSBox](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DOSBox "DOSBox") via the `scaler=advmame3x` [dosbox.conf](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Configuration_file "Configuration file") option) can be thought of as a generalization of EPX to the 3 case. The corner pixels are calculated identically to EPX.

[![AdvMAME3x/Scale3x scales pixel E into 9 new pixels](data:image/png;base64,)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Scale3x-algorithm.png "AdvMAME3x/Scale3x scales pixel E into 9 new pixels")

```
 1=E; 2=E; 3=E; 4=E; 5=E; 6=E; 7=E; 8=E; 9=E;
 IF D==B AND D!=H AND B!=F =&gt; 1=D
 IF (D==B AND D!=H AND B!=F AND E!=C) OR (B==F AND B!=D AND F!=H AND E!=A) =&gt; 2=B
 IF B==F AND B!=D AND F!=H =&gt; 3=F
 IF (H==D AND H!=F AND D!=B AND E!=A) OR (D==B AND D!=H AND B!=F AND E!=G) =&gt; 4=D
 5=E
 IF (B==F AND B!=D AND F!=H AND E!=I) OR (F==H AND F!=B AND H!=D AND E!=C) =&gt; 6=F
 IF H==D AND H!=F AND D!=B =&gt; 7=D
 IF (F==H AND F!=B AND H!=D AND E!=G) OR (H==D AND H!=F AND D!=B AND E!=I) =&gt; 8=H
 IF F==H AND F!=B AND H!=D =&gt; 9=F
```

There is also a variant improved over Scale3 called ScaleFX, developed by Sp00kyFox, and a version combined with Reverse-AA called ScaleFX-Hybrid.<sup id="cite_ref-6"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel-art_scaling_algorithms#cite_note-6"><span>[</span>6<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-7"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel-art_scaling_algorithms#cite_note-7"><span>[</span>7<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-pixelscalers_8-0"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel-art_scaling_algorithms#cite_note-pixelscalers-8"><span>[</span>8<span>]</span></a></sup>

> Eagle works as follows: for every in pixel, we will generate 4 out pixels. First, set all 4 to the color of the pixel we are currently scaling (as nearest-neighbor). Next look at the three pixels above, to the left, and diagonally above left: if all three are the same color as each other, set the top left pixel of our output square to that color in preference to the nearest-neighbor color. Work similarly for all four pixels, and then move to the next one.<sup id="cite_ref-9"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel-art_scaling_algorithms#cite_note-9"><span>[</span>9<span>]</span></a></sup>

Assume an input matrix of 33 pixels where the centermost pixel is the pixel to be scaled, and an output matrix of 22 pixels (i.e., the scaled pixel)

```
first:        |Then
. . . --\ CC  |S T U  --\ 1 2
. C . --/ CC  |V C W  --/ 3 4
. . .         |X Y Z
              | IF V==S==T =&gt; 1=S
              | IF T==U==W =&gt; 2=U
              | IF V==X==Y =&gt; 3=X
              | IF W==Z==Y =&gt; 4=Z
```

Thus if we have a single black pixel on a white background it will vanish. This is a bug in the Eagle algorithm but is solved by other algorithms such as EPX, 2xSaI, and HQ2x.

**2SaI**, short for 2 Scale and Interpolation engine, was inspired by Eagle. It was designed by Derek Liauw Kie Fa, also known as Kreed, primarily for use in console and computer [emulators](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Emulator "Emulator"), and it has remained fairly popular in this niche. Many of the most popular emulators, including [ZSNES](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ZSNES "ZSNES") and [VisualBoyAdvance](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/VisualBoyAdvance "VisualBoyAdvance"), offer this scaling algorithm as a feature. Several slightly different versions of the scaling algorithm are available, and these are often referred to as _Super 2SaI_ and _Super Eagle_.

[![](data:image/png;base64,)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Super2xSaI-matrix.svg)

The matrix of surrounding pixels that Super2xSaI uses to scale a single pixel

The 2xSaI family works on a 44 matrix of pixels where the pixel marked A below is scaled:

```
I E F J
G A B K --\ W X
H C D L --/ Y Z
M N O P
```

For 16-bit pixels, they use pixel masks which change based on whether the 16-bit pixel format is 565 or 555. The constants `colorMask`, `lowPixelMask`, `qColorMask`, `qLowPixelMask`, `redBlueMask`, and `greenMask` are 16-bit masks. The lower 8 bits are identical in either pixel format.

Two interpolation functions are described:

```
INTERPOLATE(uint32 A, UINT32 B).
-- linear midpoint of A and B
  if (A == B) return A;
  return (
    ((A &amp; colorMask) &gt;&gt; 1)
  + ((B &amp; colorMask) &gt;&gt; 1)
  + (A &amp; B &amp; lowPixelMask) );

Q_INTERPOLATE(uint32 A, uint32 B, uint32 C, uint32 D)
-- bilinear interpolation; A, B, C, and D's average
  x = ((A &amp; qColorMask) &gt;&gt; 2)
    + ((B &amp; qColorMask) &gt;&gt; 2)
    + ((C &amp; qColorMask) &gt;&gt; 2)
    + ((D &amp; qColorMask) &gt;&gt; 2);
  y = (A &amp; qLowPixelMask)
    + (B &amp; qLowPixelMask)
    + (C &amp; qLowPixelMask)
    + (D &amp; qLowPixelMask);
  y = (y &gt;&gt; 2) &amp; qLowPixelMask;
  return x + y;
```

The algorithm checks A, B, C, and D for a diagonal match such that `A==D` and `B!=C`, or the other way around, or if they are both diagonals or if there is no diagonal match. Within these, it checks for three or four identical pixels. Based on these conditions, the algorithm decides whether to use one of A, B, C, or D, or an interpolation among only these four, for each output pixel. The 2xSaI arbitrary scaler can enlarge any image to any resolution and uses bilinear filtering to interpolate pixels.

Since Kreed released<sup id="cite_ref-10"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel-art_scaling_algorithms#cite_note-10"><span>[</span>10<span>]</span></a></sup> the source code under the [GNU General Public License](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/GNU_General_Public_License "GNU General Public License"), it is freely available to anyone wishing to utilize it in a project released under that license. Developers wishing to use it in a non-GPL project would be required to rewrite the algorithm without using any of Kreed's existing code.

It is available in [DosBox](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DosBox "DosBox") via `scaler=2xsai` option.

Main article: [hqx](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hqx "Hqx")

[Maxim Stepin](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Maxim_Stepin&action=edit&redlink=1 "Maxim Stepin (page does not exist)")'s hq2x, hq3x, and hq4x are for scale factors of 2:1, 3:1, and 4:1 respectively. Each work by comparing the color value of each pixel to those of its eight immediate neighbors, marking the neighbors as close or distant, and using a pre-generated lookup table to find the proper proportion of input pixels' values for each of the 4, 9 or 16 corresponding output pixels. The hq3x family will perfectly smooth any diagonal line whose slope is 0.5, 1, or 2 and which is not anti-aliased in the input; one with any other slope will alternate between two slopes in the output. It will also smooth very tight curves. Unlike 2xSaI, it anti-aliases the output.<sup id="cite_ref-11"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel-art_scaling_algorithms#cite_note-11"><span>[</span>11<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-pixelscalers_8-1"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel-art_scaling_algorithms#cite_note-pixelscalers-8"><span>[</span>8<span>]</span></a></sup>

-   [![Image enlarged 3 with the nearest-neighbor interpolation](data:image/png;base64,)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Test_nn.png "Image enlarged 3 with the nearest-neighbor interpolation")
    
-   [![Image enlarged by 3 with hq3x algorithm](data:image/png;base64,)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Test_hq3x.png "Image enlarged by 3 with hq3x algorithm")
    
    Image enlarged by 3 with hq3x algorithm
    

hq_n_x was initially created for the [Super NES](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Super_NES "Super NES") emulator [ZSNES](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ZSNES "ZSNES"). The author of [bsnes](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bsnes "Bsnes") has released a space-efficient implementation of hq2x to the public domain.<sup id="cite_ref-12"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel-art_scaling_algorithms#cite_note-12"><span>[</span>12<span>]</span></a></sup> A port to [shaders](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shader "Shader"), which has comparable quality to the early versions of xBR, is available.<sup id="cite_ref-libretro_13-0"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel-art_scaling_algorithms#cite_note-libretro-13"><span>[</span>13<span>]</span></a></sup> Before the port, a shader called "scalehq" has often been confused for hqx.<sup id="cite_ref-14"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel-art_scaling_algorithms#cite_note-14"><span>[</span>14<span>]</span></a></sup>

There are 6 filters in this family: **xBR** , **xBRZ**, **xBR-Hybrid**, **Super xBR**, **xBR+3D** and **Super xBR+3D**.

xBR ("scale by rules"), created by Hyllian, works much the same way as HQx (based on pattern recognition) and would generate the same result as HQx when given the above pattern.<sup id="cite_ref-15"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel-art_scaling_algorithms#cite_note-15"><span>[</span>15<span>]</span></a></sup> However, it goes further than HQx by using a 2-stage set of [interpolation](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interpolation "Interpolation") rules, which better handle more complex patterns such as [anti-aliased](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anti-aliased "Anti-aliased") lines and curves. Scaled background textures keep the sharp characteristics of the original image, rather than becoming blurred like HQx (often ScaleHQ in practice) tends to do. The newest xBR versions are multi-pass and can preserve small details better. There is also a version of xBR combined with Reverse-AA shader called xBR-Hybrid.<sup id="cite_ref-16"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel-art_scaling_algorithms#cite_note-16"><span>[</span>16<span>]</span></a></sup> xBR+3D is a version with a 3D mask that only filters 2D elements.

xBRZ by Zenju is a modified version of xBR. It is implemented from scratch as a CPU-based filter in [C++](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C%2B%2B "C++") .<sup id="cite_ref-17"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel-art_scaling_algorithms#cite_note-17"><span>[</span>17<span>]</span></a></sup> It uses the same basic idea as xBR's pattern recognition and interpolation but with a different rule set designed to preserve fine image details as small as a few pixels. This makes it useful for scaling the details in faces, and in particular eyes. xBRZ is optimized for [multi-core CPUs](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multi-core_processor "Multi-core processor") and [64-bit architectures](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/64-bit_architecture "64-bit architecture") and shows 4060% better performance than HQx even when running on a single CPU core only.<sup>[<i><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources. (December 2015)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> It supports scaling images with an [alpha channel](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alpha_channel "Alpha channel"), and scaling by integer factors from 2 up to 6.

Super xBR<sup id="cite_ref-18"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel-art_scaling_algorithms#cite_note-18"><span>[</span>18<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-19"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel-art_scaling_algorithms#cite_note-19"><span>[</span>19<span>]</span></a></sup> is an algorithm developed by Hylian in 2015. It uses some combinations of known linear filters along with xBR edge detection rules in a non-linear way. It works in two passes and can only scale an image by two (or multiples of two by reapplying it and also has an anti-ringing filter). Super xBR+3D is a version with a 3D mask that only filters 2D elements. There is also a Super xBR version rewritten in C/C++.<sup id="cite_ref-20"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel-art_scaling_algorithms#cite_note-20"><span>[</span>20<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-pixelscalers_8-2"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel-art_scaling_algorithms#cite_note-pixelscalers-8"><span>[</span>8<span>]</span></a></sup>

[![](data:image/png;base64,)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Tv_rotsprite.png)

Left: Original pixel art image  
Middle: Image rotated using nearest-neighbor rotation algorithm  
Right: Image rotated using RotSprite algorithm

RotSprite is a scaling and rotation algorithm for sprites developed by Xenowhirl. It produces far fewer artifacts than nearest-neighbor rotation algorithms, and like EPX, it does not introduce new colors into the image (unlike most interpolation systems).<sup id="cite_ref-21"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel-art_scaling_algorithms#cite_note-21"><span>[</span>21<span>]</span></a></sup>

The algorithm first scales the image to 8 times its original size with a modified Scale2 algorithm which treats similar (rather than identical) pixels as matches. It then (optionally) calculates what rotation offset to use by favoring sampled points that are not boundary pixels. Next, the rotated image is created with a nearest-neighbor scaling and rotation algorithm that simultaneously shrinks the big image back to its original size and rotates the image. Finally, overlooked single-pixel details are (optionally) restored if the corresponding pixel in the source image is different and the destination pixel has three identical neighbors.<sup id="cite_ref-22"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel-art_scaling_algorithms#cite_note-22"><span>[</span>22<span>]</span></a></sup>

Fast RotSprite is a fast rotation algorithm for pixel art developed by Oleg Mekekechko for the [Pixel Studio](https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.PixelStudio) app. It is based on [RotSprite](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel-art_scaling_algorithms#RotSprite) but has better performance with slight quality loss. It can process larger images in real-time. Instead of the 8 upscale, Fast RotSprite uses a single 3 upscale. Then it simply rotates all pixels with rounding coordinates. Finally, it performs 3 downscale without introducing new colors. As all operations on each step are independent, they can be done in parallel to greatly increase performance.

The KopfLischinski algorithm is a novel way to extract resolution-independent [vector graphics](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vector_graphics "Vector graphics") from pixel art described in the 2011 paper "Depixelizing Pixel Art".<sup id="cite_ref-pixelart_23-0"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel-art_scaling_algorithms#cite_note-pixelart-23"><span>[</span>23<span>]</span></a></sup> A Python implementation is available.<sup id="cite_ref-24"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel-art_scaling_algorithms#cite_note-24"><span>[</span>24<span>]</span></a></sup>

The algorithm has been ported to GPUs and optimized for real-time rendering. The [source code](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Source_code "Source code") is available for this variant.<sup id="cite_ref-25"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel-art_scaling_algorithms#cite_note-25"><span>[</span>25<span>]</span></a></sup>

### Edge-directed interpolation (EDI)

\[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Pixel-art_scaling_algorithms&action=edit&section=12 "Edit section: Edge-directed interpolation (EDI)")\]

Edge-directed interpolation (EDI) describes upscaling techniques that use statistical sampling to ensure the quality of an image as it is scaled up.<sup id="cite_ref-26"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel-art_scaling_algorithms#cite_note-26"><span>[</span>26<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-27"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel-art_scaling_algorithms#cite_note-27"><span>[</span>27<span>]</span></a></sup> There were several earlier methods that involved detecting edges to generate blending weights for linear interpolation or classifying pixels according to their neighbor conditions and using different otherwise isotropic interpolation schemes based on the classification. Each interpolation approach boils down to weighted averages of neighboring pixels. The goal is to find the optimal weights. [Bilinear interpolation](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bilinear_interpolation "Bilinear interpolation") sets all the weights to be equal. Higher-order interpolation methods such as [bicubic](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bicubic_interpolation "Bicubic interpolation") or [sinc interpolation](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sinc_interpolation "Sinc interpolation") consider a larger number of neighbors than just the adjacent ones.

NEDI (New Edge-Directed Interpolation) computes local covariances in the original image and uses them to adapt the interpolation at high resolution. It is the prototype filter of this family.<sup id="cite_ref-:0_28-0"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel-art_scaling_algorithms#cite_note-:0-28"><span>[</span>28<span>]</span></a></sup>

EDIUpsizer<sup id="cite_ref-29"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel-art_scaling_algorithms#cite_note-29"><span>[</span>29<span>]</span></a></sup> is a resampling filter that resizes an image by a factor of two both horizontally and vertically using NEDI (new edge-directed interpolation).<sup id="cite_ref-:0_28-1"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel-art_scaling_algorithms#cite_note-:0-28"><span>[</span>28<span>]</span></a></sup> EDIUpsizer also uses a few modifications to basic NEDI to prevent a lot of the artifacts that NEDI creates in detailed areas. These include condition number testing and adaptive window size,<sup id="cite_ref-30"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel-art_scaling_algorithms#cite_note-30"><span>[</span>30<span>]</span></a></sup> as well as capping constraints. All modifications and constraints to NEDI are optional (can be turned on and off) and are user-configurable. This filter is rather slow.

FastEDIUpsizer is a slimmed-down version of EDIUpsizer that is slightly more tuned for speed. It uses a constant 88 window size, only performs NEDI on the [luma](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Luminance_(video) "Luminance (video)") plane, and only uses either bicubic or bilinear interpolation as the fallback interpolation method.

Another edge-directed interpolation filter. Works by minimizing a cost function involving every pixel in a scan line. It is slow.

EEDI2 resizes an image by 2 in the vertical direction by copying the existing image to 2y(n) and interpolating the missing field. It is intended for edge-directed interpolation for deinterlacing (i.e. not made for resizing a normal image, but can do that as well). EEDI2 can be used with both TDeint and TIVTC, see the discussion link for more info on how to do this.<sup id="cite_ref-31"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel-art_scaling_algorithms#cite_note-31"><span>[</span>31<span>]</span></a></sup>

The SuperRes<sup id="cite_ref-32"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel-art_scaling_algorithms#cite_note-32"><span>[</span>32<span>]</span></a></sup> shaders use a different scaling method which can be used in combination with NEDI (or any other scaling algorithm). The method is explained in detail by its creator Shiandow in a Doom9 forum post in 2014.<sup id="cite_ref-33"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel-art_scaling_algorithms#cite_note-33"><span>[</span>33<span>]</span></a></sup> This method often gives better results than just using NEDI, and rival those of NNEDI3. These are now also available as an MPDN renderscript.

NNEDI is a family of intra-field [deinterlacers](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deinterlacing "Deinterlacing") that can also be used for enlarging images by powers of two. When being used as a deinterlacer, it takes in a [frame](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Film_frame "Film frame"), throws away one [field](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field_(video) "Field (video)"), and then interpolates the missing pixels using only the information from the kept field. There are so far three major generations of NNEDI.

NNEDI, the original version, works with [YUY2](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/YUY2 "YUY2") and [YV12](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/YV12 "YV12") input.<sup id="cite_ref-34"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel-art_scaling_algorithms#cite_note-34"><span>[</span>34<span>]</span></a></sup> NNEDI2 added RGB24 support and a special function `nnedi2_rpow2` for upscaling. NNEDI3 extends NNEDI2 with a predictor [neural network](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Neural_network "Neural network"). Both the size of the network and the neighborhood it examines can be tuned for a speed-quality tradeoff:<sup id="cite_ref-35"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel-art_scaling_algorithms#cite_note-35"><span>[</span>35<span>]</span></a></sup>

> This is a quality vs speed option; however, differences are usually small between the number of neurons for a specific resize factor, however the performance difference between the count of neurons becomes larger as you quadruple the image size. If you are only planning on doubling the resolution then you won't see massive differences between 16 and 256 neurons. There is still a noticeable difference between the highest and lowest options, but not orders of magnitude different.<sup id="cite_ref-36"><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel-art_scaling_algorithms#cite_note-36"><span>[</span>36<span>]</span></a></sup>
